hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a one-dimensional crystal with a lattice constant $a$. The potential energy $V(x)$ for an electron in this crystal is periodic. Within a single unit cell centered at the origin, ranging from $x = -a/2$ to $x = a/2$, the potential is described by a symmetric triangular well:
$$
V(x) = \begin{cases}
-V_0 \left(1 - \frac{2|x|}{b}\right) & \text{for } |x| \le \frac{b}{2} \\
0 & \text{for } \frac{b}{2} < |x| \le \frac{a}{2}
\end{cases}
$$
where $V_0$ is a positive constant representing the depth of the well, and $b$ is the width of the well, with the constraint $b < a$. The potential is repeated periodically for all other unit cells, i.e., $V(x+na) = V(x)$ for any integer $n$.

Within the framework of the nearly-free electron model, the periodic potential acts as a perturbation on the free electron states. This perturbation opens up energy gaps at the boundaries of the Brillouin zones.

Calculate the magnitude of the first energy band gap, $E_g$, which opens at the edge of the first Brillouin zone. Express your answer as a closed-form analytic expression in terms of $V_0$, $a$, and $b$.
